            "content": {
                "raw": "My understanding is that these frontends never really worked in 2.x and were just maintenance nightmares for @MatthewTurk and others.  This is as opposed to 3.0, where the infrastructure redesign is what allowed them to actually be fully functional.  If this is truly the case, it's probably a better idea to drop them rather than keep them around and have to continually fix new issues that crop up on the mailing list when those users would be better served moving to 3.0.  @MatthewTurk should really chime in here since I think he's the only one who knows for sure.",
                "html": "<p>My understanding is that these frontends never really worked in 2.x and were just maintenance nightmares for <a href=\"/MatthewTurk/\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"@MatthewTurk\" class=\"mention\">Matthew Turk</a> and others.  This is as opposed to 3.0, where the infrastructure redesign is what allowed them to actually be fully functional.  If this is truly the case, it's probably a better idea to drop them rather than keep them around and have to continually fix new issues that crop up on the mailing list when those users would be better served moving to 3.0.  <a href=\"/MatthewTurk/\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"@MatthewTurk\" class=\"mention\">Matthew Turk</a> should really chime in here since I think he's the only one who knows for sure.</p>",
                "markup": "markdown"
            },
